in supabase where we use polar based and transport based connection :-


1) Root cause (what your log means)

During startup, Hibernate tries to run schema work (ddl-auto: update).
It needs a connection for DDL/metadata. But Supabase Session pooler refuses because:

MaxClientsInSessionMode: max clients reached - in Session mode max clients are limited to pool_size

So you’re connecting to a pooler endpoint that is in Session mode, and the pool is already full (maybe other services, dashboards, old app processes, etc.).

2) Permanent solution (best practice)
✅ A) Use Transaction Pooler for your app (runtime traffic)

In Supabase dashboard:

Go to Database → Connection pooling

Choose Transaction mode host/port

Use that host in your Spring datasource.url

Example:

spring:
  datasource:
    url: jdbc:postgresql://<TRANSACTION_POOLER_HOST>:5432/postgres?sslmode=require&prepareThreshold=0
    username: postgres.<projectref>
    password: xxxx


Important: Your current host aws-1-ap-southeast-2.pooler.supabase.com can be either session or transaction depending on what Supabase gave you. You must copy the transaction pooler host exactly from dashboard.

✅ B) Never run ddl-auto: update on pooled connections (production rule)

Industry rule: migrations are separate from app runtime.

So change:

spring:
  jpa:
    hibernate:
      ddl-auto: validate   # or none


Then run DB migrations using:

Flyway / Liquibase, OR

manually SQL (Supabase SQL editor), OR

connect using direct DB endpoint (non-pooler) for migrations.

Why? Because schema updates / metadata queries + pooler can cause startup connection spikes and failures.

✅ C) Use two connection configs (industry pattern)

Runtime (transaction pooler) + Migration (direct DB)

Runtime (application.yml):

spring:
  datasource:
    url: jdbc:postgresql://<TRANSACTION_POOLER_HOST>:5432/postgres?sslmode=require&prepareThreshold=0
    username: postgres.<projectref>
    password: xxxx
  jpa:
    hibernate:
      ddl-auto: validate


Migration profile (application-migrate.yml):

spring:
  datasource:
    url: jdbc:postgresql://db.<projectref>.supabase.co:5432/postgres?sslmode=require
    username: postgres
    password: xxxx
  jpa:
    hibernate:
      ddl-auto: update


Then you run migrations only when needed:

SPRING_PROFILES_ACTIVE=migrate (one-time)

normal app always uses runtime profile.

3) Immediate steps to fix NOW (so it starts today)

In Supabase dashboard, copy the Transaction pooler host and replace your URL host with it.

Set:

ddl-auto: validate (or none)

Keep:

prepareThreshold=0

Set Hikari:

maximum-pool-size: 1 or 2 is fine for dev

Restart your services and ensure old processes are stopped (your old runs may still hold pooler client slots).

4) Why you still see it even with max-pool-size=2

Because the pooler “max clients reached” is about pooler client slots, not your local Hikari pool only.
If you have:

multiple microservices,

multiple IntelliJ runs,

restarts,

Supabase dashboard SQL editor,

or other apps using same pooler,

you can hit the session pool limit easily.

5) One more critical thing: your URL host must match your mode

Session mode error means you are still using a session pooler host.
So paste only this part (hide project ref if you want):

the full host you’re using (just the hostname)

and tell me what Supabase dashboard shows for:

Transaction pooler host

Session pooler host

Then I’ll tell you exactly which one to use.

TL;DR permanent solution

App runtime → Transaction pooler + prepareThreshold=0

No Hibernate schema updates at runtime → use Flyway/Liquibase or run DDL with direct DB separately

ddl-auto → validate / none in normal profile

If you do just those, this error will stop permanently.


📘 Supabase Pooler + Hibernate DDL Notes (Production Understanding)
🔵 1️⃣ Supabase Connection Pooling Modes

Supabase provides two pooler modes:

Mode	Best For	Supports	Risk
Session Pooler	Long connections	Full DB features	Max client limit
Transaction Pooler	Microservices / APIs	Normal queries	No session features
🟢 Transaction Pooler (Recommended for Microservices)
✅ When to Use

Spring Boot apps

Kafka consumers/producers

Scheduled jobs

High concurrency services

Cloud deployments

✅ Why Industry Uses This

Shares DB connections efficiently

Prevents DB overload

Handles auto scaling services

Works best with stateless APIs

⚠️ Limitation

Does NOT support:

Session state

Temp tables

Prepared statement caching (needs prepareThreshold=0)

✅ Required JDBC Setting
prepareThreshold=0


👉 Prevents prepared statement session pinning
👉 Required for transaction pooler stability

🔴 Session Pooler
✅ When to Use

Legacy apps

Stateful DB sessions

Direct DB tools

Long transactions

❌ Why NOT for Microservices

Limited client slots

Easy to hit MaxClientsInSessionMode error

Not scalable

🔥 Your Error Meaning
MaxClientsInSessionMode


Means:
👉 Session pooler client slots full
👉 Not Hikari issue
👉 Not Spring issue
👉 Pooler limit reached

📘 Hibernate ddl-auto Notes
🟢 ddl-auto = validate
✅ What It Does

Checks:

Tables exist

Columns exist

Types match entity

❌ What It DOES NOT DO

Does NOT create tables

Does NOT update schema

Does NOT change DB

✅ When To Use

✔ Production
✔ Pooled DB connections
✔ Supabase transaction pooler
✔ Stable schema environments

🟡 ddl-auto = update
✅ What It Does

Hibernate automatically:

Creates missing tables

Adds new columns

Updates schema

⚠️ Risks

❌ Can break production schema
❌ Needs extra DB metadata connections
❌ Not safe with poolers
❌ Can cause startup connection spikes

✅ When To Use

✔ Local development
✔ First time schema generation
✔ Migration environment

🔴 ddl-auto = create / create-drop

Only for:

Testing

Local development

Never production

📘 Industry Standard Architecture
🟢 Runtime Application Config
spring:
 datasource:
   url: TRANSACTION_POOLER_URL
 jpa:
   hibernate:
     ddl-auto: validate

🟡 Migration / Schema Update Config
spring:
 datasource:
   url: DIRECT_DATABASE_URL
 jpa:
   hibernate:
     ddl-auto: update

📘 Why Production Uses Validate

Because:

✔ Prevents accidental schema change
✔ Works safely with poolers
✔ Avoids startup DB overload
✔ Forces proper migration process
✔ Predictable deployments

📘 Why Update Causes Pooler Problems

During startup Hibernate:

Reads metadata

Checks schema

Runs alter statements

Opens multiple connections

👉 Pooler may reject extra connections
👉 Causes startup failure

📘 Real Production Flow (Industry)
Developer → writes entity change
↓
Migration tool → applies schema change
↓
Application runtime → validate only
↓
Production safe + stable

📘 Quick Decision Guide
Environment	ddl-auto	DB Connection
Local Dev	update	Direct DB OR pooler
QA / Staging	validate	Transaction pooler
Production	validate	Transaction pooler
Migration Job	update	Direct DB
📘 Golden Rules (Remember)
⭐ Rule 1

Never run schema update through pooler in production

⭐ Rule 2

Use Transaction pooler for microservices

⭐ Rule 3

Use Validate in production runtime

⭐ Rule 4

Use Migration tools for schema changes

📘 Your Correct Production Setup
✅ JDBC
Transaction pooler host
prepareThreshold=0

✅ Hibernate
ddl-auto = validate

📘 Simple Real-Life Analogy
Session Pooler

Like reserving a table in restaurant for whole evening.

Transaction Pooler

Like ordering takeaway — fast, efficient, shared resources.

📘 Why Your Error Happened

You were:
❌ Using Session pooler
❌ Running ddl-auto update
❌ Hitting pool client limit

📘 Final Production Safe Combo
Transaction Pooler
+
prepareThreshold=0
+
ddl-auto = validate







